A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
FY 2025 Congressional Capability Upgrade funding of $5.000 million will fund the development, integration and testing of the proliferated Low Earth Orbit (pLEO)
Skyhook System and the Kraken 18 Communication Pod as federated systems onto the MH-60.

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                    FY 2024 FY 2025
Congressional Add: MH-60 Capability Upgrades                                                                              9.654   5.000
FY 2024 Accomplishments: FY 2024 funding supports the analysis and development of Modular Open
Systems Architecture (MOSA) Technical Reference Framework (TRF) to continue to develop and advance
the framework and architecture prototype for potential migration to the MH-60 during a mid-life block upgrade;
Totally Optimized Aircraft Diagnostics (TOAD) to include additional Weapons Replaceable Assemblies (WRAs)
to optimize data mining to support and improve fleet sustainment efforts; Cyber Characterization and Intrusion
Detection effort to refine the cyber baseline for the platform under an operational environment; Prototype
Minotaur Carry On/Carry Off (CO/CO) Kits to bring Minotaur capability on-board the MH-60 to correlate, process
and disseminate real-time track data that will increase the Common Operating Picture (COP).
FY 2025 Plans: FY2025 funding supports the development, integration, and testing of the pLEO Skyhook
system. Integrating the Skyhook terminal to provide Beyond Line of Sight (BLOS) data capability will ensure
the MH-60 is able to receive and contribute to a national Common Operational Picture (COP), enabling cross-
platform data sharing and supporting Artificial Intelligence/Machine Learning (Al/ML) applications to improve
COP fidelity. Funding supports the development, integration, and testing of the Kraken 18 Communication
Pod. The Kraken 18 Communication Pod will bring a secure network architecture supporting multiple enclaves
through a variety of data pathways (Joint Range Extension Applications Protocol-C (JREAP-C), Link 16, Tactical
Targeting Network Technology (TTNT), Integrated Broadcast Service (IBS), etc.) delivering a tactical hot spot for
MH-60 platforms.
